05853nam a22009735i 9783110897630DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112005gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831108976307 a10.1515/97831108976302doi  a(DE-B1597)56663  a(OCoLC)979757027  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP302.8b.K868 2005eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a401/.41222  aER 9902rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27788:1 aKupferberg, Irit, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTroubled Talk :bMetaphorical Negotiation in Problem Discourse /cIrit Kupferberg, David Green.  aReprint 2011 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (221 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage, Power and Social Process [LPSP] ,x1861-4175 ;v150 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is meaning constructed discursively by participants in problem discourse? To which discursive resources do they resort in order to accomplish their complicated tasks of problem presentation and negotiation of possible solutions? To what extent are these resources related to the interactional and meaningful construction of problems and solutions? Irit Kupferberg and David Green – a discourse analyst and a clinical psychologist – have explored naturally-occurring media, hotline, and cyber troubled discourse in a quest for answers. Inspired by a constructivist-interpretive theoretical framework grounded in linguistic anthropology, conversation analysis, narrative inquiry, and clinical psychology as well as their professional experience, the authors put forward three novel claims that are illustrated by 70 attention-holding examples. First, sufferers often present their troubles through detailed narrative discourse as well as succinct story-internal tropes such as metaphors and similes – discursive resources that constitute two interrelated versions of the troubled self. Particularly interesting are the intriguing figurative constructions produced in acute emotional states or at crucial discursive junctions. Second, such figurative constructions often 'lubricate' the interactive negotiation of solutions. Third, when the figurative and narrative resources of self-construction are employed in the public arena they are used and sometimes abused by the media representatives, depending on a plethora of contextual resources identified in this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aDiscourse analysisxPsychological aspects. 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aPsycholinguistics. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aMetapher. 4aSprachsoziologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  adiscourse analysis.  ametaphor.  asociolinguistics.1 aGreen, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Linguistics and Semiotics  2000-2014 (EN)z978311023845708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2005z9783110277111oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2005z978311027717308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LINGUISTICS 2005z978311027714208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2005z9783110276886